A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners are struggling to find the money needed to repair the down-to-earth highway infrastructure, many are finding a solution in the form of a small black box that sticks over the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record all of the miles traveled by a motorist and transmit information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government offices to reshape the outdated funding system of major U.S. roads.
The sector generally without interest in major axis planning has suddenly led to a lively debate and strong alliances.
The libertarians have joined environmental groups to put pressure on the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about privacy.
And while the members of Congress fail to agree on whether to continue, several States have not waited.
They are looking for how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay according to the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is really necessary for our nation.
“It’s not like we had the choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, CEO of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will start recording the miles traveled by each Californian driver by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don’t buy as much gas as they did before.
Cars can travel more than a mile with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gas tax is simply not tenable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a mileage payment system.
“This is the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this the cost of mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces the city liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits in a way that reduces congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the objectives set out in the state's ambitious climate warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chairman of the House of Representatives Transportation Committee, said he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
Proponents of the Reason Foundation’s free market also appreciate the idea of getting drivers paid per mile.
“It’s not just a tax getting stuck in a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits that are provided to them.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. Secretaries of Transportation who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go on the path of paying a mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have carried about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who must travel many miles every day to get to work or to the city.
However, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country’s most important experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state kilometre fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is trying a test on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with a device, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their bare facts and gestures.
“The concerns about Big Brother and this kind of thing are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads the strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something that people want.
From the start of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily walks and events.
Nevada is one of the few states that are moving away now to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact place or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, the citizens will be more comfortable.
The research of this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up named True Mileage.
Initially, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It sought to penetrate the emerging auto insurance market, in which drivers would pay according to their mileage.
But the devices it tests have been good to the big axis planners because they do not use the GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t record their speed and don’t locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of certain States.
There are far less expensive means and far less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other States hope to sell the concept to unsuspecting citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than enough.
In New York City, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking costs, provide “pay-to-drive” insurance, and create a dataset on real-time speed from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“The drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them,” said a document on urban development.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole debate on mileage payment is not just a huge diversion.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising gas taxes.
A single or annual additional tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gas, so everyone pays their fair share.
“There is no need to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the director of legislation and public affairs at the commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
