How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Have you finished typing passwords to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Director General of Morpho, even believes that “the century will be biometric”.
Only biometrics will make it possible to ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission for Computer Science and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, consumer privacy officer at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will make it possible to provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of palms or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
“For example, some people who work on concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable,” said Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand imply a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - one cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of the sensors and the computing capacity of the computers necessary for the analysis of the data, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten in the last five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but it takes a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and infallible marker, DNA also evokes hopes and concerns.
“In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data,” confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognise one person among others) and authentication (ensure that the person is what they claim to be).
To date, identification has concerned the issue of identity papers: biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) must be compared with the information that the State has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not try to usurp someone else’s identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or store.
“We recover images from surveillance cameras and compare them with photos of celebrities who are freely circulating on the Internet,” said Dany Nassif, director of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: take a photo of a quidam that makes its tail in a store, track its progression through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logic (opening a computer).
More recently, the control of presence has been added.
“A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend who points for another,” explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoul<0xC3><0xAA>me by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and signs of the big distribution: when paying in-store with his bank card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in cash for thirty seconds less, that’s appreciable,” explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
“Digital fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it,” said Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy experts, they, continue to worry about.
“The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras, and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr, or Picasa scare me the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick, Canada’s Privacy Commissioner.
