Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog’s tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies have shown that happy dogs move their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs move it more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what it was like with other species.
He added that just like in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To find out more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We introduced dogs to films that featured other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going further left or right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog move the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed a tail drifting mainly to the left (again from the dog’s point of view moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think that dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements that they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you meet several times other dogs and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The canine behavioral expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Sciences, said it was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs were more likely to go to a robot dog when its tail was going to the left rather than to the right, instead of getting anxious – the opposite of what is found in the Italian study.”
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
“Although many elements, detected in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will surely not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
