A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York has identified a new species of bush dolphin off Australia’s northern coast.
Thibaut Bouveroux, head of scientific mission at the Observatory for Conservation and the Study of Marine Animals and Environment (OCEAMM), returns to L'Express for this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Are you surprised by the discovery of this new species of bush dolphin?
That's good news, but that's not particularly surprising to me.
If in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our knowledge of the science of species classification.
Moreover, it is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are challenged because of the advances in genetics.
In the same way, two very close species were distinguished morphologically by genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific bush dolphins and the Atlantic bush whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is it a discovery of importance, as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had long been known by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered depending on the number of individuals existing on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new species discovered has emerged, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brazing limits the creation of new species.
On the contrary, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It is important to know that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
It is preferable to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Mariana cave, only 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money on the search for life on other planets than on marine research and it’s time for that to change.
